description:
[UPDATE AUGUST 2021]
Version 2.0 has been released! Check out the feature showcase here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=62TYwfzUnyo

[UPDATE JULY 2020]
Due to the fact I was not able to do a behind the scenes video in time, I am publishing the source code for the project on GitHub: https://github.com/MarkusMaal/BlueScreenSimulatorPlus

This is a little program I've created that allows you to simulate blue screens from different Windows operating systems. There are also a lot of customization options, command line options, hacks, codes and a lot more.

Download links: https://github.com/MarkusMaal/BlueScreenSimulatorPlus/releases
Mirror link: https://bit.ly/3em1Whl
Website: http://markustegelane.eu
Random video: http://markustegelane.eu/random.html

comments.text:
Version 2.121 released!
What's new
* CRITICAL 2.121 PATCH *
* Fixed save configurations button not working
* Version from GitHub contains dots in place of spaces, which the updated update manager should be able to handle

* 2.12 changelog *
+ You can now close blue screens by pressing Escape or F7, in addition to Alt+F4
* Updated to .NET 4.8
* Improved blue screen generation speed
* Changed the name of the executable to "Blue screen simulator plus.exe"
* Automatically switch to night mode if Windows dark mode is active
* Changed default update server to markustegelane.eu
* Minor bug fixes

Upgrade from a previous version
Open any version of blue screen simulator plus. If you are using a 1.x version, you'll automatically be prompted that a new version is available. If not, go to settings and check for updates. If you are using 2.x or later, you may need to change your update server. Select one, which says "markustegelane.tk" and if it isn't listed, select a custom server and set it to "http://markustegelane.tk/app ". Then you can check for updates. Select "Yes" to start the update process.

Download if you don't have a previous version installed:
Download the .exe from here: https://github.com/MarkusMaal/BlueScreenSimulatorPlus/releases/tag/2.121
comments.author: @markusTegelane

comments.text: Is it safe? I've seen alot of people getting concerned about this.
comments.author: @Casethrey

comments.text:
It's safe, here are some reasons why:
1) The code is open source, you can have a look at what it's doing yourself
2) Some AVs also detect so called "scareware", which also includes blue screen simulators and automatically mark them as malware (even tough this software will not run unless you read and hit "Yes" on the dialog that pops up when you launch the application for the first time, so it cannot be used as part of a malware payload without significant code changes)
3) Web browsers tend to block it sometimes, because it's "not a commonly downloaded file", but that'll happen with anything that isn't commonly downloaded
4) People who get concerned ran it through VirusTotal, which will find some false positives due to what I mentioned before and automatically assume it's a virus (it's not)

comments.text:
This very first version does actually try to create a folder on C: drive due to a bug in the Verifile verification subsystem. This is fixed with newer versions (2.0 and later). This could be why a higher number of these anti-malware programs detect these false-positives. The purpose of verifile is to generate a text file with a hash file, which is generated based on the hardware on your computer. It is not spyware, because NONE of this data is sent back to me (it's open source on GitHub, you can verify that's the case and all of these AV engines are WRONG, apart from ones that say Riskware.BSOD, because yes, this program is literally designed to generate blue screens, but you agree to not use it maliciously when first launching it on any PC).

I'm tired of trying to explain this, but AV products are NOT the final authority for whether a file is safe or not, threat detections are just an indication to make further investigations.

I put the latest version (2.13) through VirusTotal and it only had 5/73 detections, which isn't a lot and indicates a false positive (hash: 72e8c82be402fb8927d02f71dfd90fce6c63e8c89736bdd24281078e9c2ba42a).

comments.text:
Version 2.0 released!
I'll release a new video soon, but you can update to this version right now (you should get a notification asking you to update when the program is launched with an internet connection, if not then select 'Check for updates' in the settings window)

Changelog:
+ Added Windows 11 error screen
+ Added Windows 1.x/2.x blue screen (with the beeping noise option)
+ Added 'Replace "PC" with "device"' option for Windows 10 blue screen
+ Added ability to choose the culprit file from a list, instead of specifying one manually
+ Added 'Additional error codes' option for Windows 10 blue screen
+ Added 'Show additional information about file' option for Windows XP/Vista/7 blue screens
+ Added night theme
+ Added online + offline user manual
+ Added the ability to specify every file and code displayed on the Windows NT blue screen
+ Added 'Dump' option for Windows XP-7 blue screens
+ Added a loading bar when generating the Windows NT blue screen
+ Added USB device trigger to prank mode
+ Added the ability to change the update server
+ Added multiple display support and behaviour options (e.g. mirror, blank other screens, etc.)
+ Added the ability to add and remove operating systems/presets
+ Added the option to reset all settings for one preset
+ Horizonal and vertical margin options for Windows 8+ error screens
+ More customization options for Windows Vista/7 blue screen
+ Display an error message, when there is no internet connection, when trying to check for updates
+ Disable ALT+F4 option for certain error screens when using prank mode
+ Dropdown menu interface
+ Added "Source code", "Copying", and "Random factoid" buttons to the about screen
+ GPLv3 license
* Changed the font for Windows 8/10 blue screens (from Segoe UI to Segoe UI Semilight)
* Large overhaul of the source code (reduced spaghetti code, each error screen is stored in a class object)
* 'Hacks' renamed to 'Additional options'
* Each operating system now has isolated configurations, meaning all settings applied on one error screen will only be for that one error screen specifically
* Corrected the name of Windows CE blue screen from "Windows CE 3.0 or later" to "Windows CE 5.0 or later"
* New configuration file format (incompatible with 1.x versions)
* Backwards compatibility with 1.x configuration files
* Updated layout for the about screen
* Updated icon and logo
* No need to manually disable ClearType for Windows XP and CE error screens (that's done automatically now)
* New splash screen
* Fixed the "complete" text in Windows 8+ error screens ('N% complete') and in Windows Vista/7 blue screens ('Physical memory dump complete')
* Buttons specific toward the current error screen are displayed in the flow menu instsead of the bottom area
* Updated system requirements with more precise information
* The program doesn't lock up when launching a blue screen
* Fixed the ' symbol in Windows 3.1 blue screen
* Updater 1.1 (update system)
	+ The 'vercheck.txt' file gets hidden, when checking for updates
	+ Display an error message when there is no internet connection available
	* Minor modifications during the update process
* Verifile 1.1 (computer verification system)
	* The first use message is displayed right as the application is launched (without even displaying the splash screen)
	* A different file is used for system verification
	* More forgiving in terms of verification failures
	- Doesn't create a folder directly on the C: drive anymore (which may cause an error message when launching the program)
* Streamlined command line options (now relies heavily on a configuration file)
* Changed codename from Bluesmith to Waffles
- Removed prank mode button (instead now only found in the dropdown menus)
- Removed OS selector, also save, load, and reset buttons from the additional options menu (moved to 'Simulator settings' menu)
- Removed the hide OS option from 'Simulator settings' (useless, since you can now just remove operating systems from the list)
- Removed dark mode easter egg (unneeded, since there is now night theme)
? Added an easter egg for the new Windows 1.x/2.x blue screen
? Something embarrassing
? Windows Boot Manager
? Dangerous egg!!!

Comment edit: Changed "Less forgiving" to "More forgiving"

comments.text: The program is designed in a way that it won't start without a popup message (basically telling the other person that this program is a simulator and giving them an option to exit) if you log in as a different user. Also, pressing Ctrl+Alt+Del will work, unlike real blue screens. And there are also other subtle ways to tell these blue screens are fake (such as with the Win10 bsod, the percentage moves at a constant speed until 60% and then speeds up). The program also advises the user to not use this program maliciously. I do not condone this sort of activity and I am not responsible for what you do with this software - you are.

comments.text: Yes, it is safe, tough I dont blame you for asking, since the software was closed source at first. The reason why I kept the source code private for a while was to prevent malware authors from bypassing the warning that pops up when you first launch the program (basically, I didnt want anyone to make scareware using my program). I have since learned that this effort was completely pointless, because any .NET winforms program can be easily decompiled using software such as dotPeek. So, in order to increase the credibility of this program, I published the source and added the GPLv3 license to it. The very first commit of the source is in fact pretty much identical to the one shown in this video with a few minor differences, such as "complite" was changed to "complete", etc.

comments.text:
What? This isn't what the program is actually doing. It does add a file into your user folder, which may trigger this prompt. It is a harmless text document that contains the fingerprint for the computer it started on. If you have the know-how or someone else you know can read C# source code, you may check the source code and even recompile it to confirm it isn't harmful. I may check the download link later today to verify it isn't hijacked or something. TL;DR probably a false positive from your AV
Edit: Versions 1.x have a bug, where Verifile writes a text document to C:\mas (which is probably what it was detecting), but that was fixed with later versions. General advice is to avoid 1.x, because it's buggy and full of spaghetti code.
